                        <div class="muscle-text bd-bot exercise-list-start">
                            <h3><strong>Hip Abductors</strong></h3><p>The primary hip abductor muscles include the gluteus minimus, gluteus medius, and tensor fasciae latae. The piriformis and sartorius are considered secondary hip abductors.</p><p>The hip abductors move the legs away from the midline of the body. When the legs are fixed to the ground, the hip abductors function to stabilize the torso. A good example would be when standing on one leg.</p><p>During the cable hip abduction, they function to bring the leg away from the midline against resistance. As this happens, the opposite hip flexor functions to keep a stable position for the non-working leg.</p><p>In a similar exercise that used side stepping, the hip abductors showed an <a href="https://www.jospt.org/doi/full/10.2519/jospt.2015.5888" target="_blank" rel="nofollow noopener">activation rate of 45.2%</a>. This was specifically in the tensor fasciae latae.</p>                        </div>
                    </div>
                </div>
